<section xml:id="lesson-02">
  <title>Lesson 2 - Linear Functions</title>

  <remark>
    <p>No explicit learning objectives were provided in the original lesson.</p>
  </remark>

  <exercises>

    <exercise xml:id="l2-slope-intercept">
      <statement>
        <p>Give the slope and <m>y</m>-intercept of each line whose equation is given, then graph the line.</p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>y=\frac{7}{2}x-2</m></li>
          <li><m>x=5</m></li>
          <li><m>y=-3x</m></li>
          <li><m>y=-1</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Identify the slope and intercept from each equation and sketch the corresponding line.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="l2-intercepts">
      <statement>
        <p>Use the intercepts to graph each line whose equation is given.</p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>x+y=-3</m></li>
          <li><m>3x+4y=12</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Find the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-intercepts and graph each line.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="l2-application">
      <statement>
        <p>
          You are looking to expand your candy store. You currently rent a small,
          <m>1150</m> square foot space for <m>\$2731.25</m> per month.
          The owner of the shop next door pays <m>\$3562.50</m> for a
          <m>1500</m> square foot space.
          Another shop that you estimate to be <m>2000</m> square feet will be available
          at the end of next month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Write a linear function that models the rent, <m>R</m>, as a function of the square
          footage, <m>x</m>, then estimate the cost of the <m>2000</m> square foot space.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Use the given data points to determine a linear model and evaluate it at <m>x=2000</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  </exercises>
</section>
